{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:52:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:52:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14766"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14766"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.89,0.05,0.03,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65200"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50637"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5186"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65200"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESecond generation antipsychotic medications (including olanzapine, clozapine, risperidone, quetiapine, and aripiprazole) are widely prescribed for the treatment of schizophrenia and other psychiatric conditions. These medications, unlike first generation antipsychotics (such as haloperidol and chlorpromazine), can significantly affect metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most common metabolic complication of second generation antipsychotic medications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weight gain","Type 2 diabetes","Elevated triglycerides","Elevated total cholesterol","Elevated uric acid"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeight gain\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common metabolic complication of second generation antipsychotics, affecting up to 80% of patients. It typically occurs within the first few months of treatment and often precedes other metabolic changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other complications are less common:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E develops in some patients, usually after significant weight gain has occurred\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated total cholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E are important but less frequent complications that typically develop later in treatment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated uric acid\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant direct complication of second generation antipsychotics\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of metabolic complications is highest with clozapine and olanzapine. Regular monitoring of weight, blood glucose and lipids is essential for all patients taking these medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-generation antipsychotics include haloperidol and chlorpromazine, while second generation includes olanzapine, clozapine, and risperidone","Second generation antipsychotics commonly cause weight gain as their primary metabolic side effect, affecting up to 80% of patients","Weight gain typically precedes other metabolic complications like diabetes and dyslipidaemia","Clozapine and olanzapine carry the highest risk of metabolic complications among second-generation antipsychotics"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50637"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14766"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50637"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:30:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:33:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65200"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta